  <discussion>Rhynchospora harperi is most abundant in a very special habitat referred to here as
        the “Hypericum pond.” These are typically shallow ponds in pine savannas, frequently ringed
        by stands of Nyssa, Taxodium, Ilex, and Cyrilla, but most of the pond itself is dominated by
        one or more myriandrous shrubby Hypericum species. Here R. harperi is distinguished from
        other species by the often abrupt bend of its ultimate internode.</discussion>
